How much is car insurance in North Carolina? 

The average cost of car insurance in North Carolina is $1,831 annually for full coverage and $579 annually for state-required minimum coverage. North Carolina car insurance rates are typically well below the national average costs of car insurance, which are $2,671 per year for full coverage and $806 per year for minimum coverage. To break down how much car insurance is in North Carolina, Bankrates insurance editorial team, which includes licensed agents, turned to Quadrant Information Services and reviewed average rates for the largest companies in the state by market share.

Key takeaways

  • The average cost of full coverage car insurance in North Carolina is $1,831 per year or $153 per month. Minimum coverage is $579 per year or $48 per month.
  • On average, North Carolina drivers pay 32 percent less for full coverage car insurance compared to the national average.
  • Of all age groups, 16-year-old drivers pay the most for car insurance in NC.
  • On average, drivers convicted of a DUI in North Carolina pay 300 percent more for full coverage compared to the state average.

North Carolina car insurance rates by city

Car insurance rates vary by state; they can also vary by city. This is why figuring out how much car insurance is in North Carolina requires more information than just your vehicle make and model. For example, Fayetteville and Charlottes average annual full coverage premiums are slightly higher than the state average. 

Larger cities tend to have higher insurance costs for a few reasons. Higher medical care costs may increase bodily injury liability payouts, and higher costs for vehicle repairs and labor may increase property damage liability, comprehensive coverage and collision coverage payouts. Additionally, larger cities tend to have more traffic, which could lead to a higher likelihood of accidents. In contrast, if you reside in a ZIP code with few vehicle thefts and accident claims, you may be able to take advantage of lower-than-average rates.

Average car insurance costs by age and gender in North Carolina

Car insurance rates vary by age in most states, including North Carolina, with younger drivers usually paying more for coverage due to a higher likelihood of accidents and subsequent claims. Recognizing and responding to sudden road hazards is a learned skill that takes time to develop, which is why teen drivers who lack driving experience typically face the highest insurance rates.

In most cases, young drivers can save money by staying on their parents policies as additional drivers for as long as possible. Premiums generally decrease with age but may begin to increase again when drivers reach their senior years. In some states, male drivers see higher average rates than female drivers, but North Carolina car insurance laws do not allow the use of gender as an insurance rating factor.

Bankrates take: Insurance rates are based on risk and statistical data. Historically, men tend to have riskier driving behavior than women. In fact, Insurance Institute for Highway Safety data reveal that men are less likely to wear a seat belt and more likely to drive while intoxicated and speed. Males tend to average more miles on the road per year than their female counterparts, as well. However, North Carolina, California, Hawaii, Massachusetts, Michigan and Pennsylvania prohibit the use of gender as a rating factor when pricing policies.

Cost considerations for young drivers in North Carolina

If a young driver is still living in their parents household, its usually cheaper to keep that driver listed on their parents policy. By staying on their parents policy, new drivers get the fiscal benefit of having more experienced drivers on the policy to keep the cost lower. You can see from the rates here that the newest drivers those who are 16 and 17 years old pay the highest average rates. Premiums may start to lower after just one year of driving experience, provided the young driver maintains a clean driving record.

How does driving record impact the cost of car insurance in North Carolina?

Safe drivers usually enjoy the cheapest car insurance. Policyholders who are caught driving without insurance in North Carolina or who have driving incidents on their records may be viewed as high-risk drivers, which often results in higher premiums. The severity of the infraction, other marks on your record and the insurance company you choose can all affect how much car insurance is in NC. A driving under the influence (DUI) conviction has the most significant impact on your premiums in North Carolina. The table here provides an overview of the average annual premium increase for a North Carolina policyholder with a single speeding ticket, accident or DUI on their record.

North Carolina car insurance rates by vehicle type

The type of vehicle you drive is another impacting rating factor for North Carolina car insurance. Vehicles that have a higher statistical likelihood of an accident, fewer safety features or more expensive repair costs may cost more to insure. For example, a BMW 330i costs about 12 percent more than the state average to insure for full coverage, while a Ford F-150 costs about 8 percent less than the state average.

How to save on car insurance in North Carolina

Generally, North Carolina car insurance is cheaper than comparable coverage in many other states. However, there are still ways to potentially shave more money off your premium.

  • Shop around: Each car insurance company calculates rates in a slightly different way, which is why your insurance premium can vary from company to company. In order to find the lowest possible premium, it may help to request quotes from several companies. Specify the same coverage types, policy limits and deductibles in order to do an apples-to-apples comparison.
  • Bundle your policies: Bundling your auto and home insurance with the same company usually makes you eligible for a multi-policy discount. This is generally one of the most significant discounts you can get. Some companies offer a bundling discount for auto and renters, condo, mobile home or life insurance, if you dont own a home, though the discount may be less.
  • Maintain a clean driving record: Drivers with incidents like tickets, at-fault accidents and DUI convictions pay quite a bit more for car insurance coverage, on average. Practicing safe driving habits may help you avoid these costly surcharges. You could save even more by allowing your insurer to track your driving behaviors through a telematics program.
  • Look for discounts: In addition to bundling, most car insurance companies offer at least a handful of discount opportunities. Some of the most common include multi-car, paperless billing and claims-free discounts.

Keep in mind that North Carolina prohibits many common discounts, though. One example is the good student discount. The state also doesnt allow insurers to offer programs that have the potential to raise a policyholders premium (like some telematics programs).

To ensure youre taking advantage of the discounts that are available, talk to your agent or a representative from your company.

Frequently asked questions

  • The best car insurance company in North Carolina for you depends on various factors. When calculating your rates, companies consider everything from your driving record to your annual mileage. If you have prior incidents like an at-fault accident or speeding ticket, you may want to focus on insurers offering coverage to high-risk drivers in order to secure the lowest premium. With certain infractions, youll also want to seek a provider that handles SR-22 certificates. Meanwhile, drivers who have multiple cars in the driveway may want to find an insurer offering a multi-car discount. And if you drive fewer than 10,000 miles per year, consider pay-per-mile insurance. Evaluating your coverage needs and driving profile can help you find the best North Carolina auto insurance company for you.

  • Although the cheapest insurance provider is different for everyone, Bankrates insurance editorial team found that State Farm, Progressive and North Carolina Farm Bureau are among the cheapest car insurance companies in North Carolina for full coverage. Keep in mind that your personal demographics, insurance coverage and discount eligibility all play a role in how much you pay for your insurance premium.

  • The average cost of car insurance in North Carolina is $1,831 per year for a full coverage policy, making the average monthly cost about $153. Minimum coverage costs an average of $579 per year, which comes out to about $36 per month. For comparison, the national monthly averages are $168 for full coverage and $48 for minimum coverage.

  • For full coverage, North Carolina car insurance rates are, on average, 32 percent less than the national average. However, cost is relative. Rates vary by driver depending on personal factors such as claims history, driving record, vehicle type, etc. If the cost you are paying is straining your budget, speak with a licensed agent, review discounts and shop with other providers to find coverage and rates that work for you.

  • Premium
    A premium is the amount the policyholder pays to the insurance company, typically on a monthly, semi-annual or annual basis, to maintain an active insurance policy.
    Full coverage car insurance
    Full coverage car insurance provides physical damage coverage for your own vehicle. It typically includes comprehensive and collision coverage in addition to state-mandated liability coverage.
    Deductible
    A deductible is the amount the policyholder agrees to pay out-of-pocket before the insurance company begins to cover expenses related to a claim.

If otherwise specified, the base profile has been modified with the following driver characteristics:

Other profiles

  • Rates were calculated based on the following insurance credit tiers assigned to our drivers: poor, average, good (base) and excellent. Insurance credit tiers factor in your official credit scores but are not dependent on that variable alone. Four states prohibit or limit the use of credit as a rating factor in determining auto insurance rates: California, Hawaii, Massachusetts and Michigan. 

     

  • Rates were calculated by evaluating our base profile with the following incidents applied: clean record (base), at-fault accident, single speeding ticket, single DUI conviction and lapse in coverage.

  • Rates were calculated by evaluating our base profile with the following differences in mileage: 2K, 5K, 12K (base), 15K and 20K.

  • Unless otherwise stated, rates are for 2023 vehicle models. For new vs used vehicles, we included the following year in our calculations: 2013.

  • Rates were calculated by evaluating our base profile with the ages 18-70 (base: 40 years) applied. Depending on age, drivers may be a renter or homeowner. Age is not a contributing rating factor in Hawaii and Massachusetts due to state regulations. For teen drivers, rates were determined by adding a 16- or 17-year-old teen to their 40-year-old married parents' policy. The rates displayed reflect the total cost of a driver this age added to their parents policy. 

  • The following states do not use gender as a determining factor in calculating premiums: California, Hawaii, Massachusetts, Michigan, North Carolina, Pennsylvania.

  • Rates were evaluated based on the following marital/family status: single (base), married, 40-year-old married man and woman. Marital status is not a rating factor in Hawaii and Massachusetts.
